## A Record-Setting Month?

April 2026 is shaping up to be a month to remember, though not for the right reasons. With 59 recalls reported already and counting, we're looking at an upward trajectory that might rival previous records from late last year.

### The Latest Headlines

On April 8th alone, 11 new recalls were issued. Headlining these, Lone Star Dairy Products LLC revealed a Class I recall for their spray dried dairy powder due to Salmonella contamination. This is not just a hypothetical risk--Salmonella poisoning can be severe, especially for vulnerable populations.

*
Pocas International Corp. had a flurry of Class III recalls due to compromised packaging on their 'Popping Boba RTD' line. While this is a less severe classification, it still raises questions about quality control.
*
JFE Franchising Inc faced the music with multiple Class II recalls after glass shards were discovered in their dumpling products. Never thought you'd need a dental guard for snack time.

### The Year in Numbers

So far in 2026, we have witnessed 302 total recalls, starkly close to becoming a record-setting year. Breaking it down:
- **Class I recalls** (high risk): 84
- **Class II recalls** (moderate risk): 193
- **Class III recalls** (low risk): 25

Notably, 64 recalls this year involved repeat offenders, including several of our 'worst brands' culprits.

### Brands to Watch

- Moonlight Packing Corporation: 11 recalls, all Class I--one wonders about their internal QA.
- Albertsons Companies LLC: the grocery giant isn't faring much better with a similar record.

Still, they have stiff competition. CHETAK NEW YORK LLC continues their streak, holding the dubious honor of leading in total recalls.

### The Takeaway

Stay sharp, readers. Food safety isn't guaranteed, and vigilance is your first line of defense. Check your pantries, read labels, and don't hesitate to contact the manufacturer if something seems off. Until tomorrow, keep your shelves--and your wits--about you.
